        "# 1. What is hypothesis testing in statistics?\n",
        "  - Hypothesis testing in statistics is a method used to make decisions or inferences about a population based on sample data. It helps determine whether there is enough evidence in a sample to support a particular belief or claim about a population parameter.\n",
        "\n",
        "  üîç Key Concepts:\n",
        "\n",
        "  1. Null Hypothesis (H‚ÇÄ):\n",
        "  A statement that there is no effect or no difference. It's the assumption that nothing has changed.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  2. Alternative Hypothesis (H‚ÇÅ or Ha):\n",
        "  A statement that there is an effect or a difference. It is what you want to prove.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  3. Test Statistic:\n",
        "  A value calculated from the sample data that is used to test the hypothesis.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  4. P-value:\n",
        "  The probability of obtaining test results at least as extreme as the observed results, assuming the null hypothesis is true.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  5. Significance Level (Œ±):\n",
        "  A threshold (commonly 0.05) set by the researcher to determine whether the p-value is small enough to reject the null hypothesis.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  ‚úÖ Steps in Hypothesis Testing:\n",
        "\n",
        "  1. State the null and alternative hypotheses.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  2. Choose the significance level (Œ±).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  3. Collect sample data and calculate the test statistic.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  4. Find the p-value or critical value.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  5. Compare and make a decision:\n",
        "\n",
        "  If p-value ‚â§ Œ±, reject H‚ÇÄ (evidence supports H‚ÇÅ).\n",
        "\n",
        "  If p-value > Œ±, fail to reject H‚ÇÄ (not enough evidence for H‚ÇÅ).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  üìå Example:\n",
        "\n",
        "  Suppose a company claims that the average delivery time is 30 minutes. You want to test if the actual delivery time is different.\n",
        "\n",
        "  H‚ÇÄ: Œº = 30 (no difference)\n",
        "\n",
        "  H‚ÇÅ: Œº ‚â† 30 (there is a difference)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  You collect sample data and run the test. If the result shows a p-value less than 0.05, you reject H‚ÇÄ and conclude that the delivery time is significantly different from 30 minutes.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  "
      ],

        "# 2. What is the null hypothesis, and how does it differ from the alternative hypothesis?\n",
        "    -‚úÖ What is the Null Hypothesis and How It Differs from the Alternative Hypothesis?\n",
        "\n",
        "    In hypothesis testing, two opposing statements are made to test a theory or claim using sample data:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    ---\n",
        "\n",
        "    üîπ 1. Null Hypothesis (H‚ÇÄ):\n",
        "\n",
        "    It is the default or starting assumption.\n",
        "\n",
        "    States that there is no effect, no difference, or no relationship.\n",
        "\n",
        "    It assumes the status quo or existing belief is true.\n",
        "\n",
        "    The goal is often to test whether we have enough evidence to reject it.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    Example:\n",
        "    H‚ÇÄ: The average exam score = 50\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    ---\n",
        "\n",
        "    üîπ 2. Alternative Hypothesis (H‚ÇÅ or Ha):\n",
        "\n",
        "    It is the statement we want to test or prove.\n",
        "\n",
        "    Suggests that there is an effect, a difference, or a relationship.\n",
        "\n",
        "    If data provides strong evidence, we reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    Example:\n",
        "    H‚ÇÅ: The average exam score ‚â† 50\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    ---\n",
        "\n",
        "    üîÑ Key Differences:\n",
        "\n",
        "    Feature\tNull Hypothesis (H‚ÇÄ)\tAlternative Hypothesis (H‚ÇÅ)\n",
        "\n",
        "    Meaning\tNo change or effect\tThere is a change or effect\n",
        "    Purpose\tStarting point for testing\tWhat we want to prove\n",
        "    Symbol\tH‚ÇÄ\tH‚ÇÅ or Ha\n",
        "    Decision\tMay be rejected or not\tMay be accepted if H‚ÇÄ is rejected\n",
        "    Based on\tExisting belief or assumption\tResearch or observation-based claim\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    ------\n",
        "\n",
        "    üìå Summary:\n",
        "\n",
        "    H‚ÇÄ assumes nothing has changed.\n",
        "\n",
        "    H‚ÇÅ is a claim that challenges H‚ÇÄ.\n",
        "\n",
        "    Hypothesis testing evaluates whether the sample data is strong enough to reject H‚ÇÄ and support H‚ÇÅ.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "    "
      ],

        "# 3. Explain the significance level in hypothesis testing and its role in deciding the outcome of a test.\n",
        "   -‚úÖ Significance Level in Hypothesis Testing and Its Role\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üîπ What is Significance Level (Œ±)?\n",
        "\n",
        "   The significance level, denoted by Œ± (alpha), is a threshold value used in hypothesis testing to decide whether to reject the null hypothesis (H‚ÇÄ).\n",
        "\n",
        "   It represents the maximum probability of making a Type I error ‚Äî that is, rejecting H‚ÇÄ when it is actually true.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üî¢ Common Values of Œ±:\n",
        "\n",
        "   0.05 (5%) ‚Äì most commonly used\n",
        "\n",
        "   0.01 (1%) ‚Äì more strict\n",
        "\n",
        "   0.10 (10%) ‚Äì more lenient\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üéØ Role in Hypothesis Testing:\n",
        "\n",
        "   1. Compare p-value to Œ±:\n",
        "\n",
        "   If p-value ‚â§ Œ± ‚Üí Reject H‚ÇÄ\n",
        "\n",
        "   If p-value > Œ± ‚Üí Fail to reject H‚ÇÄ\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   2. It defines the ‚Äúcritical region‚Äù:\n",
        "\n",
        "   Outcomes in this region are considered statistically significant.\n",
        "\n",
        "   It helps set boundaries for decision-making.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üß† Example:\n",
        "\n",
        "   Suppose you're testing whether a new drug is more effective than the old one:\n",
        "\n",
        "   H‚ÇÄ: The new drug is equally effective.\n",
        "\n",
        "   H‚ÇÅ: The new drug is more effective.\n",
        "\n",
        "   You choose Œ± = 0.05 (5%).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   If the p-value from your test is 0.03:\n",
        "\n",
        "   Since 0.03 < 0.05, you reject H‚ÇÄ.\n",
        "\n",
        "   This means there's statistically significant evidence that the new drug is better.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   ‚ö†Ô∏è Why is Significance Level Important?\n",
        "\n",
        "   Controls the risk of false positives.\n",
        "\n",
        "   Balances confidence and risk in decision-making.\n",
        "\n",
        "   Helps researchers standardize their conclusions.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üìå Summary:\n",
        "\n",
        "   Significance level (Œ±) is the cutoff for deciding whether the result is statistically significant.\n",
        "\n",
        "   It helps determine whether to accept or reject the null hypothesis.\n",
        "\n",
        "   Lower Œ± = more strict; higher Œ± = more lenient.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "  \n"
      ],

        "# 4.What are Type I and Type II errors? Give examples of each.\n",
        "   - ‚úÖ What are Type I and Type II Errors?\n",
        "\n",
        "   In hypothesis testing, errors can occur when making decisions based on sample data. These errors are classified as:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üîπ 1. Type I Error (False Positive):\n",
        "\n",
        "   Definition: Rejecting the null hypothesis (H‚ÇÄ) when it is actually true.\n",
        "\n",
        "   In simple words: You think there is an effect or difference, but there actually isn't.\n",
        "\n",
        "   Controlled by: The significance level (Œ±).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   üìå Example:\n",
        "   A medical test shows a person has a disease when they actually do not have it.\n",
        "\n",
        "   > Null Hypothesis (H‚ÇÄ): The person does not have the disease.\n",
        "   You reject H‚ÇÄ ‚Üí say the person is sick ‚Üí But they are actually healthy.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üîπ 2. Type II Error (False Negative):\n",
        "\n",
        "   Definition: Failing to reject the null hypothesis (H‚ÇÄ) when it is actually false.\n",
        "\n",
        "   In simple words: You think there is no effect or difference, but there actually is.\n",
        "\n",
        "   Controlled by: The power of the test (1 - Œ≤).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   üìå Example:\n",
        "   A medical test shows a person does not have a disease when they actually do.\n",
        "\n",
        "   > Null Hypothesis (H‚ÇÄ): The person does not have the disease.\n",
        "   You do not reject H‚ÇÄ ‚Üí say the person is healthy ‚Üí But they are actually sick.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üìä Summary Table:\n",
        "\n",
        "   Error Type\tDecision Made\tReality\tExample\n",
        "\n",
        "   Type I\tReject H‚ÇÄ (claim something)\tH‚ÇÄ is actually true\tHealthy person diagnosed as sick\n",
        "   Type II\tFail to reject H‚ÇÄ (claim nothing)\tH‚ÇÄ is actually false\tSick person diagnosed as healthy\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   "
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "SAQw69IS1s5Q"
      }

        "# 5.What is the difference between a Z-test and a T-test? Explain when to use each.\n",
        "   - ‚úÖ Difference Between Z-test and T-test & When to Use Each\n",
        "\n",
        "   Both Z-test and T-test are statistical tests used to compare sample data with a population or between groups ‚Äî but they are used in different situations based on sample size and known information.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üîπ Z-test:\n",
        "\n",
        "   Used When:\n",
        "\n",
        "   The sample size is large (n ‚â• 30).\n",
        "\n",
        "   The population standard deviation (œÉ) is known.\n",
        "\n",
        "   Data is approximately normally distributed.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   Common Use:\n",
        "\n",
        "   Comparing sample mean to population mean.\n",
        "\n",
        "   Comparing proportions between two groups.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   üìå Example:\n",
        "   Testing whether the average height of students is different from the national average, with known population standard deviation.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üîπ T-test:\n",
        "\n",
        "   Used When:\n",
        "\n",
        "   The sample size is small (n < 30).\n",
        "\n",
        "   The population standard deviation is unknown.\n",
        "\n",
        "   Data is normally distributed or nearly normal.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   Types:\n",
        "\n",
        "   One-sample t-test (compare sample mean to population mean)\n",
        "\n",
        "   Independent two-sample t-test (compare means of two independent groups)\n",
        "\n",
        "   Paired t-test (compare means from the same group at different times)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   üìå Example:\n",
        "   Testing whether a new teaching method improved student scores in a class of 20 students, with unknown population standard deviation.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üß† Key Differences Summary:\n",
        "\n",
        "   Feature\tZ-test\tT-test\n",
        "\n",
        "   Sample size\tLarge (n ‚â• 30)\tSmall (n < 30)\n",
        "   Population std. dev (œÉ)\tKnown\tUnknown\n",
        "   Distribution\tNormal\tt-distribution (fatter tails)\n",
        "   Use case\tProportions or large samples\tSmall .samples, unknown œÉ\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   ---\n",
        "\n",
        "   üéØ Final Tip:\n",
        "\n",
        "   Use Z-test when œÉ is known and sample is large.\n",
        "\n",
        "   Use T-test when œÉ is unknown or sample is small.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "   "
      ],

        "# 7.Implement hypothesis testing using Z-statistics for a sample dataset inPython. Show the Python code and interpret the results.\n",
        "sample_data = [49.1, 50.2, 51.0, 48.7, 50.5, 49.8, 50.3, 50.7, 50.2, 49.6,\n",
        "50.1, 49.9, 50.8, 50.4, 48.9, 50.6, 50.0, 49.7, 50.2, 49.5,\n",
        "50.1, 50.3, 50.4, 50.5, 50.0, 50.7, 49.3, 49.8, 50.2, 50.9,\n",
        "50.3, 50.4, 50.0, 49.7, 50.5, 49.9]\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from scipy.stats import norm\n",
        "\n",
        "# Given sample data\n",
        "sample_data = [49.1, 50.2, 51.0, 48.7, 50.5, 49.8, 50.3, 50.7, 50.2, 49.6,\n",
        "               50.1, 49.9, 50.8, 50.4, 48.9, 50.6, 50.0, 49.7, 50.2, 49.5,\n",
        "               50.1, 50.3, 50.4, 50.5, 50.0, 50.7, 49.3, 49.8, 50.2, 50.9,\n",
        "               50.3, 50.4, 50.0, 49.7, 50.5, 49.9]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 1: Known population parameters\n",
        "population_mean = 50\n",
        "population_std = 0.5  # Assumed known\n",
        "alpha = 0.05          # Significance level\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 2: Sample statistics\n",
        "n = len(sample_data)\n",
        "sample_mean = np.mean(sample_data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 3: Z-statistic calculation\n",
        "z_stat = (sample_mean - population_mean) / (population_std / np.sqrt(n))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 4: P-value calculation for two-tailed test\n",
        "p_value = 2 * (1 - norm.cdf(abs(z_stat)))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 5: Display the results\n",
        "print(\"Sample Mean:\", round(sample_mean, 4))\n",
        "print(\"Z-Statistic:\", round(z_stat, 4))\n",
        "print(\"P-Value:\", round(p_value, 4))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 6: Decision\n",
        "if p_value < alpha:\n",
        "    print(\"‚úÖ Reject the null hypothesis: Significant difference found.\")\n",
        "else:\n",
        "    print(\"‚ùå Fail to reject the null hypothesis: No significant difference.\")"
      ],

        "# 8.Write a Python script to simulate data from a normal distribution and calculate the 95% confidence interval for its mean. Plot the data using Matplotlib.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "from scipy import stats\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 1: Simulate data from a normal distribution\n",
        "np.random.seed(0)  # for reproducibility\n",
        "mean = 100\n",
        "std_dev = 15\n",
        "sample_size = 100\n",
        "data = np.random.normal(loc=mean, scale=std_dev, size=sample_size)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 2: Calculate sample mean and standard error\n",
        "sample_mean = np.mean(data)\n",
        "standard_error = stats.sem(data)  # Standard error of the mean\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 3: Calculate 95% confidence interval\n",
        "confidence = 0.95\n",
        "confidence_interval = stats.t.interval(confidence, df=sample_size-1, loc=sample_mean, scale=standard_error)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 4: Display results\n",
        "print(f\"Sample Mean: {sample_mean:.2f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"95% Confidence Interval: ({confidence_interval[0]:.2f}, {confidence_interval[1]:.2f})\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 5: Plot the histogram with confidence interval\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))\n",
        "plt.hist(data, bins=15, edgecolor='black', alpha=0.7, color='skyblue')\n",
        "plt.axvline(sample_mean, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Mean = {sample_mean:.2f}')\n",
        "plt.axvline(confidence_interval[0], color='green', linestyle='--', label=f'95% CI Lower = {confidence_interval[0]:.2f}')\n",
        "plt.axvline(confidence_interval[1], color='green', linestyle='--', label=f'95% CI Upper = {confidence_interval[1]:.2f}')\n",
        "plt.title(\"Histogram of Simulated Normal Data with 95% Confidence Interval\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Value\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Frequency\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.grid(True)\n",
        "plt.show()"

        "# 9.Write a Python function to calculate the Z-scores from a dataset and visualize the standardized data using a histogram. Explain what the Z-scores represent in terms of standard deviations from the mean.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Sample dataset\n",
        "data = [72, 85, 90, 65, 70, 88, 95, 78, 82, 76, 80, 84, 91, 69, 74]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Calculate Z-scores in one line\n",
        "z_scores = [(x - np.mean(data)) / np.std(data) for x in data]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot histogram of Z-scores\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))\n",
        "plt.hist(z_scores, bins=10, color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')\n",
        "plt.axvline(0, color='red', linestyle='--', label='Z = 0 (Mean)')\n",
        "plt.title(\"Histogram of Z-scores\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Z-score\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Frequency\")\n",
        "plt.grid(True)\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Print Z-scores\n",
        "print(\"Z-scores:\", np.round(z_scores, 2))"
      ],
